e solution, the network shows a clear methodological pathway: sample preparation followed by reagent addition. This procedural grounding is important because it ties the reagent’s color-change behavior to a repeatable test method rather than an isolated chemical fact. [Data: Entities (335, 312); Relationships (327, 285)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Amylase is the transformation agent in the community, converting starch into maltose and affecting iodine-test outcomes\",\"explanation\":\"Amylase is described as an enzyme used in the activity to break down starch into maltose, and it is noted as present in the digestive system while also being experimentally added from a filtered solution made from ground germinating green gram (mung) seedlings. [Data: Entities (348, 358); Relationships (353, 351)]\\n\\nThe dataset states that starch is converted to maltose by the amylase enzyme, explaining why the iodine–starch color reaction can disappear when starch is digested. This creates a coherent chain: amylase-driven conversion reduces intact starch, which in turn removes the iodine-based positive signal. [Data: Entities (348, 362, 312); Relationships (351, 285)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Germinating mung seedlings provide a practical biological source for preparing amylase used in the activity\",\"explanation\":\"Germinating green gram (mung) seedlings are identified as the source material used to prepare a filtered amylase solution. The relationship explicitly links these seedlings to amylase preparation via filtering a solution made from ground seedlings. [Data: Entities (358, 348); Relationships (353)]\\n\\nThis establishes a concrete supply chain within the community: a biological substrate (germinating seedlings) is processed to obtain an enzymatic reagent (amylase), which is then applied to starch to produce maltose and alter test results. [Data: Entities (358, 348, 240, 362); Relationships (353, 351)]\"},{\"summary\":\"The white porcelain tile is a supporting laboratory surface used in